time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses two pointers, `start` and `end`, to split the string into k-sized chunks. It then swaps the characters at these pointers and increments/decrements them accordingly. The `swap` method is used to swap characters at the pointers. The time complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the string, as we iterate through the string once to perform the swaps. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the pointers and the `swap` method. The energy implications are low because the algorithm operates efficiently without consuming excessive resources.

